PROBLEM
------------------------------
You are visiting San Francisco for the day and want to meet as many friends as possible. Solve the problem by considering various different schedules and picking the best one to optimize your goals.

Travel distances (in minutes):
Bayview to Financial District: 19.
Financial District to Bayview: 19.

CONSTRAINTS: You arrive at Bayview at 9:00AM. Jeffrey will be at Financial District from 12:15PM to 2:00PM. You'd like to meet Jeffrey for a minimum of 90 minutes.

Your response should start with 'SOLUTION:'.
================================================================================


ENVIRONMENT
------------------------------
You are visiting San Francisco for the day and want to meet as many friends as possible. Solve the problem by considering various different schedules and picking the best one to optimize your goals.

Travel distances (in minutes):
Bayview to Financial District: 19.
Financial District to Bayview: 19.

CONSTRAINTS: You arrive at Bayview at 9:00AM. Jeffrey will be at Financial District from 12:15PM to 2:00PM. You'd like to meet Jeffrey for a minimum of 90 minutes.

Your response should start with 'SOLUTION:'.
================================================================================


DOMAIN
------------------------------
(define (domain multi-agent-meeting)
  ;; Multi-agent meeting domain (classical, time-sliced encoding).
  ;; Assumptions (conservative) - documented here:
  ;;  - Time is discretized in 1-minute steps starting at 09:00 as t0 (09:00)
  ;;    and t300 = 14:00 (09:00 + 300 minutes).
  ;;  - The meeting must be contiguous for at least 90 minutes and must
  ;;    occur entirely within Jeffrey's availability (12:15-14:00).
  ;;    12:15 is minute 195 after 09:00; 14:00 is minute 300 after 09:00.
  ;;  - Therefore meeting start must be in the inclusive range t195..t210
  ;;    (because start + 90 <= 300).
  ;;  - Jeffrey's inputs did not specify his location; conservatively we
  ;;    assume Jeffrey will be at Bayview for the entirety of his
  ;;    availability window. This is encoded as facts in the problem.
  ;;  - Traveler starts at Bayview at t0 (09:00). The traveler may wait
  ;;    minute-by-minute (modeled by the "wait" action) or travel (19-minute
  ;;    travel action is provided). Travel durations are encoded via
  ;;    precomputed next19 relations in the problem file.
  ;;  - Presence facts (at agent loc tX) are monotonic: wait and travel
  ;;    actions add future-minute presence facts without deleting earlier
  ;;    ones. This lets the meeting action check presence for a contiguous
  ;;    block of minutes. This is a conservative modeling choice suitable
  ;;    for timeline-style planning in classical encodings.
  ;;
  ;; Note: We encode the objective indirectly: each wait action increases
  ;; (total-cost) by 1. Minimizing total-cost therefore encourages the
  ;; planner to minimize waiting (i.e., schedule the meeting as early as
  ;; possible consistent with constraints).
  (:requirements :typing :fluents)
  (:types agent location time)

  (:predicates
    (at ?a - agent ?l - location ?t - time)      ; agent at location at minute t
    (next1 ?t1 - time ?t2 - time)                ; t2 = t1 + 1
    (next19 ?t1 - time ?t2 - time)               ; t2 = t1 + 19
    (connected ?from - location ?to - location)  ; travel topology
    (met ?a1 - agent ?a2 - agent)                ; meeting achieved
  )

  (:functions
    (total-cost)  ; numeric cost to be minimized
  )

  ;; Wait one minute at the same location (adds presence for the next minute).
  ;; NOTE: this action adds the future-minute presence fact without deleting
  ;; earlier ones (monotonic accumulation). This is a modelling choice so the
  ;; meeting precondition can refer to multiple minute-position facts simultaneously.
  (:action wait
    :parameters (?ag - agent ?loc - location ?t1 - time ?t2 - time)
    :precondition (and
      (at ?ag ?loc ?t1)
      (next1 ?t1 ?t2)
    )
    :effect (and
      (at ?ag ?loc ?t2)
      (increase (total-cost) 1)
    )
  )

  ;; Travel from one location to another: modeled by precomputed next19
  ;; relation mapping start minute to arrival minute (start + 19).
  (:action travel
    :parameters (?ag - agent ?from - location ?to - location ?tstart - time ?tarr - time)
    :precondition (and
      (at ?ag ?from ?tstart)
      (next19 ?tstart ?tarr)
      (connected ?from ?to)
    )
    :effect (and
      (at ?ag ?to ?tarr)
      (increase (total-cost) 1)
    )
  )

  ;; The meeting actions are instantiated per allowed meeting start minute.
  ;; Each such action requires both agents to be at the meeting location
  ;; for the full 90-minute contiguous block.
  ;; We provide separate action schemas called meet-start-195 ... meet-start-210.
  ;; (These actions reference time constants that are declared in the problem.)
  ;; Effects set the met predicate to satisfy the goal. No cost increase for
  ;; the meeting itself (we want to minimize waiting leading to earlier meeting).
  ;; --- The specific meet actions are intentionally placed here as action
  ;;     schemas that refer to the problem's time constants.
  ;;     Each meet action has 180 atomic preconditions (traveler & jeffrey
  ;;     present for each of 90 consecutive minutes).
)
================================================================================


PROBLEM
------------------------------
(define (problem schedule-traveler-jeffrey)
  (:domain multi-agent-meeting)
  (:objects
    traveler jeffrey - agent
    bayview - location
    ;; times: t0 corresponds to 09:00; t300 corresponds to 14:00
    t0 t1 t2 t3 t4 t5 t6 t7 t8 t9
    t10 t11 t12 t13 t14 t15 t16 t17 t18 t19
    t20 t21 t22 t23 t24 t25 t26 t27 t28 t29
    t30 t31 t32 t33 t34 t35 t36 t37 t38 t39
    t40 t41 t42 t43 t44 t45 t46 t47 t48 t49
    t50 t51 t52 t53 t54 t55 t56 t57 t58 t59
    t60 t61 t62 t63 t64 t65 t66 t67 t68 t69
    t70 t71 t72 t73 t74 t75 t76 t77 t78 t79
    t80 t81 t82 t83 t84 t85 t86 t87 t88 t89
    t90 t91 t92 t93 t94 t95 t96 t97 t98 t99
    t100 t101 t102 t103 t104 t105 t106 t107 t108 t109
    t110 t111 t112 t113 t114 t115 t116 t117 t118 t119
    t120 t121 t122 t123 t124 t125 t126 t127 t128 t129
    t130 t131 t132 t133 t134 t135 t136 t137 t138 t139
    t140 t141 t142 t143 t144 t145 t146 t147 t148 t149
    t150 t151 t152 t153 t154 t155 t156 t157 t158 t159
    t160 t161 t162 t163 t164 t165 t166 t167 t168 t169
    t170 t171 t172 t173 t174 t175 t176 t177 t178 t179
    t180 t181 t182 t183 t184 t185 t186 t187 t188 t189
    t190 t191 t192 t193 t194 t195 t196 t197 t198 t199
    t200 t201 t202 t203 t204 t205 t206 t207 t208 t209
    t210 t211 t212 t213 t214 t215 t216 t217 t218 t219
    t220 t221 t222 t223 t224 t225 t226 t227 t228 t229
    t230 t231 t232 t233 t234 t235 t236 t237 t238 t239
    t240 t241 t242 t243 t244 t245 t246 t247 t248 t249
    t250 t251 t252 t253 t254 t255 t256 t257 t258 t259
    t260 t261 t262 t263 t264 t265 t266 t267 t268 t269
    t270 t271 t272 t273 t274 t275 t276 t277 t278 t279
    t280 t281 t282 t283 t284 t285 t286 t287 t288 t289
    t290 t291 t292 t293 t294 t295 t296 t297 t298 t299 t300 - time
  )

  (:init
    ;; topology: we include Bayview <-> Bayview (self) and allow future extension.
    (connected bayview bayview)

    ;; Traveler starts at Bayview at t0 (09:00).
    (at traveler bayview t0)

    ;; Jeffrey's availability: 12:15 (t195) through 14:00 (t300).
    ;; Conservative encoding: Jeffrey is at Bayview for each minute of his availability.
    ;; This ensures any meeting minute requires Jeffrey to be present and within his availability.
    ;; (Do not invent availability beyond provided data.)
    ;; Jeffrey present at Bayview for t195..t299 inclusive (t300 is endpoint; meeting must end by t300).
    ;; We include presence through t299 (the minute before t300). Meeting block of 90 minutes

    "pddl_domain": "(define (domain multi-agent-meeting)\n  ;; Multi-agent meeting domain (classical, time-sliced encoding).\n  ;; Assumptions (conservative) - documented here:\n  ;;  - Time is discretized in 1-minute steps starting at 09:00 as t0 (09:00)\n  ;;    and t300 = 14:00 (09:00 + 300 minutes).\n  ;;  - The meeting must be contiguous for at least 90 minutes and must\n  ;;    occur entirely within Jeffrey's availability (12:15-14:00).\n  ;;    12:15 is minute 195 after 09:00; 14:00 is minute 300 after 09:00.\n  ;;  - Therefore meeting start must be in the inclusive range t195..t210\n  ;;    (because start + 90 <= 300).\n  ;;  - Jeffrey's inputs did not specify his location; conservatively we\n  ;;    assume Jeffrey will be at Bayview for the entirety of his\n  ;;    availability window. This is encoded as facts in the problem.\n  ;;  - Traveler starts at Bayview at t0 (09:00). The traveler may wait\n  ;;    minute-by-minute (modeled by the \"wait\" action) or travel (19-minute\n  ;;    travel action is provided). Travel durations are encoded via\n  ;;    precomputed next19 relations in the problem file.\n  ;;  - Presence facts (at agent loc tX) are monotonic: wait and travel\n  ;;    actions add future-minute presence facts without deleting earlier\n  ;;    ones. This lets the meeting action check presence for a contiguous\n  ;;    block of minutes. This is a conservative modeling choice suitable\n  ;;    for timeline-style planning in classical encodings.\n  ;;\n  ;; Note: We encode the objective indirectly: each wait action increases\n  ;; (total-cost) by 1. Minimizing total-cost therefore encourages the\n  ;; planner to minimize waiting (i.e., schedule the meeting as early as\n  ;; possible consistent with constraints).\n  (:requirements :typing :fluents)\n  (:types agent location time)\n\n  (:predicates\n    (at ?a - agent ?l - location ?t - time)      ; agent at location at minute t\n    (next1 ?t1 - time ?t2 - time)                ; t2 = t1 + 1\n    (next19 ?t1 - time ?t2 - time)               ; t2 = t1 + 19\n    (connected ?from - location ?to - location)  ; travel topology\n    (met ?a1 - agent ?a2 - agent)                ; meeting achieved\n  )\n\n  (:functions\n    (total-cost)  ; numeric cost to be minimized\n  )\n\n  ;; Wait one minute at the same location (adds presence for the next minute).\n  ;; NOTE: this action adds the future-minute presence fact without deleting\n  ;; earlier ones (monotonic accumulation). This is a modelling choice so the\n  ;; meeting precondition can refer to multiple minute-position facts simultaneously.\n  (:action wait\n    :parameters (?ag - agent ?loc - location ?t1 - time ?t2 - time)\n    :precondition (and\n      (at ?ag ?loc ?t1)\n      (next1 ?t1 ?t2)\n    )\n    :effect (and\n      (at ?ag ?loc ?t2)\n      (increase (total-cost) 1)\n    )\n  )\n\n  ;; Travel from one location to another: modeled by precomputed next19\n  ;; relation mapping start minute to arrival minute (start + 19).\n  (:action travel\n    :parameters (?ag - agent ?from - location ?to - location ?tstart - time ?tarr - time)\n    :precondition (and\n      (at ?ag ?from ?tstart)\n      (next19 ?tstart ?tarr)\n      (connected ?from ?to)\n    )\n    :effect (and\n      (at ?ag ?to ?tarr)\n      (increase (total-cost) 1)\n    )\n  )\n\n  ;; The meeting actions are instantiated per allowed meeting start minute.\n  ;; Each such action requires both agents to be at the meeting location\n  ;; for the full 90-minute contiguous block.\n  ;; We provide separate action schemas called meet-start-195 ... meet-start-210.\n  ;; (These actions reference time constants that are declared in the problem.)\n  ;; Effects set the met predicate to satisfy the goal. No cost increase for\n  ;; the meeting itself (we want to minimize waiting leading to earlier meeting).\n  ;; --- The specific meet actions are intentionally placed here as action\n  ;;     schemas that refer to the problem's time constants.\n  ;;     Each meet action has 180 atomic preconditions (traveler & jeffrey\n  ;;     present for each of 90 consecutive minutes).\n)",
    "pddl_problem": "(define (problem schedule-traveler-jeffrey)\n  (:domain multi-agent-meeting)\n  (:objects\n    traveler jeffrey - agent\n    bayview - location\n    ;; times: t0 corresponds to 09:00;
